Provides a minimal, dependency-free JSON writer for the `steno` crate: an insertion-ordered string‚Üístring map (`OrderedMap`, mimicking JS object key ordering) plus a serializer (`to_json`) that reproduces `JSON.stringify`'s exact output for that shape. This exists so Rust-generated JSON byte-for-byte matches what the original TypeScript tool would emit, for diffing/golden-test purposes against the TS implementation elsewhere in the repo ‚Äî any change to escaping or layout here will desync that comparison.

Key behavioral details an editor must preserve: `to_json` emits `"{}\n"` for an empty map (not `"{\n}\n"`), and for non-empty maps writes one `"key": "value"` pair per line, comma-separated except after the last entry, with a trailing `}\n`. Key order follows first-insertion order via `OrderedMap`'s internal `order: Vec<String>` ‚Äî re-inserting an existing key updates its value in place but does not move its position (matches JS object semantics). String escaping (`push_json_string`) covers `"`, `\`, `\n`, `\r`, `\t`, and all other control characters below `0x20` via `\u00XX` (always two hex digits, lowercase, zero-padded ‚Äî `push_control_escape`); characters ‚â• `0x20` are passed through unescaped, including non-ASCII, so this is not full `\uXXXX`-escaping of all non-ASCII like some JSON serializers do ‚Äî it only escapes ASCII control codes, matching `JSON.stringify`'s actual behavior.

Public API: `OrderedMap::new/insert/get/len/is_empty/iter`, `json_string(s: &str) -> String` (quotes+escapes a single string for callers building richer JSON shapes than the flat map), and `to_json(map: &OrderedMap) -> String`. No other file's format is parsed against this one within the crate shown, but the comment block states the output must match TS's `JSON.stringify` exactly ‚Äî any consumer/golden file comparing against TS-generated JSON depends on this exact line/spacing layout.